06376nam a22009375i 9781575068862DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750688627 a10.1515/97815750688622doi  a(DE-B1597)583834  a(OCoLC)1253313746  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a296.7/40901422300aFamily and Household Religion :bToward a Synthesis of Old Testament Studies, Archaeology, Epigraphy, and Cultural Studies /ced. by Ruediger Schmitt, Saul M. Olyan, Rainer Albertz, Beth Alpert Nakhai. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume is the most recent collective contribution of a group of biblical scholars and archaeologists who are engaged in an ongoing debate about the nature of family and household religion in ancient Israel and its environment. It is intended to complement the volume Household and Family Religion in Antiquity, edited by John Bodel and Saul M. Olyan, which grew out of a conference held at Brown University in 2005 on household and family religion in the ancient Mediterranean world, with an emphasis on cross-cultural comparison. Several meetings after the Brown conference carried the theme forward, and a fourth meeting at Westfälische Wilhelms-Universität Münster in April 2009 emphasized theoretical and methodological challenges facing scholars of household and family religion (e.g., the conceptualization of family/household religion, the problem of identifying pertinent artifacts, and the difficulties inherent in using texts together with material evidence). This volume is a direct outgrowth of the Münster meeting.For both the meeting and the volume, the goal was to bring together a group of specialists in biblical studies, epigraphy, and archaeology who would utilize a variety of humanistic and social-scientific approaches to the data and would also be willing to engage in dialogue and debate; during the conference in Münster, there was much vigorous intellectual engagement. The essays published here reflect the energy of that conference and will contribute, both individually and collectively, to the advancement of our knowledge of Israelite family and household religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFamiliesxCongressesxHistoryxPalestine. 0aFamiliesxCongressesxReligious aspectsxJudaismxTo 70 A.D. 0aFamiliesxCongressesxReligious life. 0aFamiliesxReligious aspectsxJudaismyTo 70 A.DvCongresses. 0aFamiliesxReligious lifevCongresses. 0aFamilieszPalestinexHistoryvCongresses. 0aJewish familiesxConduct of lifexHistoryyTo 70 A.DvCongresses. 0aJewish familiesxCongressesxConduct of lifexHistoryxTo 70 A.D. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAckerman, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbertz, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbertz, Rainer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBen-Shlomo, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunimovitz, Shlomo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarol, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaviau, P. M. Michèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDever, William G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaust, Avraham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerstenberger, Erhard S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris